n, Shropshire, England":"Whittington, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"about 1130–about 1174":"about 1130–about 1174","1130–1174":"1130–1174","1132–1162":"1132–1162","1135–1187":"1135–1187","–1161":"–1161","–Female":"Deceased","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1158–Male":"1158–Deceased","1160–1187":"1160–1187","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1169–Male":"1169–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","about 1160":"about 1160","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1132":"1132","1174":"1174","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1169":"1169","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","about 1158":"about 1158","about 1169":"about 1169","about 1156":"about 1156","about 1165":"about 1165","about 1130":"about 1130","about 1174":"about 1174","Whittington, Shropshire, England":"Whittington, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gronwy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Gronow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronow","meanings":["Welsh: relationship name from the Welsh personal name  <i>Goronwy</i> (also found as  <i>Gronw</i> and  <i>Gronow</i>, from Old Welsh  <i>Guorgonui</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger ap Gronwy of Powys was born about 1130, in Shropshire, England as the son of Gronwy ap Tudur. He had at least 6 sons and 1 daughter with Mrs Roger Powys. He died about 1174, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1130–about 1174":"umbes 1130–umbes 1174","1130–1174":"1130–1174","1132–1162":"1132–1162","1135–1187":"1135–1187","–1161":"–1161","–Female":"Surnud","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–1187":"1160–1187","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1132":"1132","1174":"1174","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1169":"1169","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","about 1158":"umbes 1158","about 1169":"umbes 1169","about 1156":"umbes 1156","about 1165":"umbes 1165","about 1130":"umbes 1130","about 1174":"umbes 1174","Whittington, Shropshire, England":"Whittington, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1130–about 1174":"noin 1130–noin 1174","1130–1174":"1130–1174","1132–1162":"1132–1162","1135–1187":"1135–1187","–1161":"–1161","–Female":"Kuollut","1156–1200":"1156–1200","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1160–1187":"1160–1187","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","about 1160":"noin 1160","1165":"1165","1187":"1187",